# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: french-ironclad-gloire
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The **8×50mmR Lebel** (8mm Lebel) (designated as the **8 × 51 R Lebel** by the C.I.P.) rifle cartridge was the first smokeless powder cartridge to be made and adopted by any country.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11×59mmR Gras black powder cartridge, the smokeless 8mm Lebel cartridge started a revolution in military rifle ammunition.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Standard 8mm Lebel military ammunition was also the first rifle ammunition to feature a spitzer boat tail bullet (*balle* D), which was adopted in 1898.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The long-range ballistic performance of the 8mm Lebel bullet itself was exceptional for its time.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] For use in the magazine tube-fed early Lebel rifle, the 8 mm case was designed to protect against accidental percussion inside the tube magazine by a circular groove around the primer cup which caught the tip of the following pointed bullet.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] However, the shape of its rimmed bottle-necked case, having been designed for the Lebel rifle's tube magazine, also precluded truly efficient vertical stacking inside a vertical magazine.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The bolt thrust of the 8mm Lebel is relatively high compared to many other service rounds used in the early 20th century.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Although it was once revolutionary, the 8mm Lebel was declared obsolete after World War I and was soon after replaced with the 7.5×54mm French round.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] There were two historical commercially available 8mm Lebel cartridges: one for the Lebel Model 1886 rifle, and one for the Modèle 1892 revolver.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] They are two entirely different cartridges and are not interchangeable.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The term "8mm Lebel" for the French Mle 1892 revolver ammunition, is only applied outside France for commercial reasons and has nothing to do with the Lebel rifle.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] However, the term "8mm Lebel", used to identify a rifle cartridge, is widely recognized to distinguish the French rifle cartridge from other 8 mm rifle cartridges, such as the 8×50mmR Mannlicher cartridge used by Austria-Hungary and its successor states.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The cartridge for the tube-fed long arm was originally loaded with a 15.0 g (232 grains) cupro-nickel-jacketed, lead-cored, flat-nosed, wadcutter-style bullet, called "*balle M*", which had been designed by Lieutenant Colonel Nicolas Lebel.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The flat point (flat nose or tip) of this bullet had been designed to be safe inside the newly commissioned rifle's tube magazine.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] It was propelled by the first practical smokeless, nitrocellulose-based powder (*Poudre B*), as developed by Paul Vieille in 1884.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The ballistic performance and range of *balle M* with the new propellant eclipsed all the previous military ammunitions in existence at the time (1886).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] This *balle M* was replaced in 1898 by a new design, a 12.8 g (198 grains) 90/10 bronze mono-metal, pointed (spitzer) boat-tail bullet called "*balle D*", which provided a flatter trajectory and improved long-range performance.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Designed at the Atelier de Puteaux (APX) by Captain Georges Desaleux, the *balle D* was the first pointed *and* boat-tailed bullet to be placed into service by any military.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Later on in 1912, the round was improved into the *balle D am* ("am" stands for "*amorçage modifié*" or "modified primer"), done by crimping the primer in more deeply to prevent primer expulsions when fired in machine guns.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] This ammunition was in near-universal service during World War I (1914–1918) in all Lebel-caliber weapons.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The *balle D am* ammunition was followed in 1932 by *balle N* ammunition, which featured a lead-cored, cupro-nickel-over-steel-jacketed, pointed boat-tail bullet weighing 15.0 g (232 grains).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] It was thicker (8.3 mm instead of 8.17) and was held into a case that had a slightly larger neck diameter than that for the older *balle D am* ammunition.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The new *balle N* was again heavier than the *balle D am*, and had been designed to improve the long-range performance of the issued Hotchkiss machine guns.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Rechambering practically all French Lebel-caliber rifles and carbines to use the "N"-type ammunition was carried out during the 1930s.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] A *balle T* (tracer ammunition) and *balle P* armor-piercing rounds were also produced, along with blank and reduced charge cartridges.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] In order to safely accommodate pointed (spitzer) bullets inside the Lebel rifle magazine, a circular groove was machined around each primer cup at the case base on both *balle D am* and *balle N* ammunitions.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The role of that circular groove is to receive the pointed bullet tip of the following round loaded inside the tube magazine, and keep it *at the side* of the case base of the previous cartridge, so the tip does not easily slide to the base center where the primer is located.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The tapered form of the case itself did help too to keep pointed tips away from the primer cup of a round in front of another in the tube.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Furthermore, all *balle D* and *balle M* French military ammunitions featured *convex primer covers* which are crimped in over the primer itself.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Those small covers are not noticeable, but do provide a second effective protection against accidental primer percussion inside the Lebel's tube magazine.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Wartime experiences (1914–1918) involving hundreds of millions of Lebel rounds fired in combat have entirely confirmed the effectiveness of these protections.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] While revolutionary for its time in terms of ballistic performance, the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge had its drawbacks.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Formed by necking down the 11mm Gras rifle cartridge case, it was an odd design, with a thick rim and a rapid double taper.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] This made it more difficult to feed from standard magazine firearms such as the Berthier rifles and the Chauchat machine guns, and is the reason for the distinct curvature in the magazines of those firearms.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The Lebel rifle from which it was fired was also rather outdated by the time *balle D*, let alone the *balle N*, came along.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] A *balle N* round can only be fired from Lebel or Berthier rifles, if the chamber has been reamed to accept the larger neck of the N-type cartridge.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Such weapons are stamped *N* on top of the barrel, just in front of the receiver and behind the rear sight.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The *balle N* ammunition is identifiable by the fact that the bullet, while pointed like the solid-brass *balle D*, is lead-cored and jacketed with soft steel.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] While newly manufactured 8×50mmR Lebel ammunition has become available in the U.S., reloadable cartridge cases can also be produced by reforming .348 Winchester brass.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The 8mm Lebel round produced by Prvi Partizan is of excellent quality and replicates the performance of the original round.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] However, Privi Partizan's *older style* brass cases lack the circular groove around the primer cup, so reloaders use round-nosed or flat-nosed bullets when producing handloads for the tube-magazine Lebel rifles with these cases.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] The older Privi Partizan cases loaded with spire point bullets should only be fired single shot.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] More recently, Privi Partizan manufactured Lebel ammunition with spitzer bullets do incorporate the circular groove at the base, and are safe when stacked in the box-magazine of Berthier rifles and the tubular magazine of Lebel rifles.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] Newer cases with circular groove follow the *balle D* specifications, and shooters may use the magazine for loading.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] 1929 (7.5 French) cartridge was introduced.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/8mm-lebel] This made the 8×50mmR Lebel cartridge obsolete, but due to post-World War I financial constraints and political neglect, it was not introduced as a rifle cartridge until the adoption, just before World War II, of the MAS-36 rifle.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The purpose of ammunition is to project a force against a selected target to have an effect (usually, but not always, lethal).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] An example of ammunition is the firearm cartridge, which includes all components required to deliver the weapon's effect in a single package.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Until the 20th century, black powder was the most common propellant used, but it has now been replaced in nearly all cases by modern compounds.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Ammunition comes in a wide range of sizes and types and is often designed to work only with specific weapon systems.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] However, there are internationally recognized standards for certain ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) that enable their use across different weapons and by different users.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] There are also specific types of ammunition that are designed to have a specialized effect on a target, such as armor-piercing shells and tracer ammunition, used only in certain circumstances.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Ammunition is commonly labeled or colored in a specific manner to assist in its identification and to prevent the wrong ammunition types from being used accidentally or inappropriately.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The term *ammunition* dates back to the mid-17th century.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The word comes from the French *la munition*, for the material used for war.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] *Ammunition* and *munition* are often used interchangeably, although *munition* now usually refers to the actual weapons system with the ammunition required to operate it.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] In some languages other than English ammunition is still referred to as munition, such as: Dutch ("*munitie*"), French ("*munitions*"), German ("*Munition*"), Italian ("*munizione*") and Portuguese ("*munição*").
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Ammunition design has evolved throughout history as different weapons have been developed and different effects required.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Historically, ammunition was of relatively simple design and build (e.g., sling-shot, stones hurled by catapults), but as weapon designs developed (e.g., rifling) and became more refined, the need for more specialized ammunition increased.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Modern ammunition can vary significantly in quality but is usually manufactured to very high standards.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] For example, ammunition for hunting can be designed to expand inside a target, maximizing the damage inflicted by one round.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Anti-personnel shells are designed to fragment into many pieces and can affect a large area.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Armor-piercing rounds are specially hardened to penetrate armor, while smoke ammunition creates a fog that screens people from view.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] More generic ammunition (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO) can often be modified slightly to achieve a more specific effect (e.g., tracer, incendiary), whilst larger explosive rounds can be altered by using different fuzes.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The term *fuze* refers to the detonator of an explosive round or shell.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The spelling is different in British English and American English (fuse/fuze respectively), and they are unrelated to a fuse (electrical).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] A fuse was earlier used to ignite the propellant (e.g., such as on a firework) until the advent of more reliable systems, such as the primer or igniter that is used in most modern ammunition.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The fuze of a weapon can be used to alter how the ammunition works.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] These allow a single ammunition type to be altered to suit the situation it is required for.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] There are many fuze designs, ranging from simple mechanical to complex radar- and barometric-based systems.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Fuzes are typically armed by the acceleration force of firing the projectile and are armed several meters after clearing the weapon's bore.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] This helps to ensure the ammunition is safer to handle when loading into the weapon and reduces the chance of the detonator firing before the ammunition has cleared the weapon.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The propellant is the component of ammunition that is activated inside the weapon and provides the kinetic energy required to move the projectile from the weapon to the target.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] In recent years, compressed gas, magnetic energy, and electrical energy have been used as propellants.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Until the 20th century, gunpowder was the most common propellant in ammunition.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] However, it has since been replaced by a wide range of fast-burning compounds that are more reliable and efficient.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The propellant charge is distinct from the projectile charge, which is activated by the fuze, which causes the ammunition effect (e.g., the exploding of an artillery round).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The cartridge is the container that holds the projectile and propellant.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Not all ammunition types have a cartridge case.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] In its place, a wide range of materials can be used to contain the explosives and parts.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] With some large weapons, the ammunition components are stored separately until loaded into the weapon system for firing.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] With small arms, caseless ammunition can reduce the weight and cost of ammunition and simplify the firing process, increasing the firing rate, but the technology is still maturing and has functional issues.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The projectile is the part of the ammunition that leaves the weapon and affects the target.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] This effect is usually either kinetic (e.g., as with a standard bullet) or explosive.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] An ammunition dump is a military facility for storing live ammunition and explosives to be distributed and used at a later date.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Such a storage facility is extremely hazardous, with a high risk of accidents during unloading, packing, and transferring the ammunition.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] In the event of a fire or explosion, the site and its surrounding area are immediately evacuated, and the stored ammunition is left to detonate completely, with limited firefighting attempts from a safe distance.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] In large facilities, there may be a flooding system to extinguish a fire or prevent an explosion automatically.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Typically, an ammunition dump will have a large buffer zone surrounding it to avoid casualties in the event of an accident.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] There will also be perimeter security measures in place to prevent unauthorized personnel from accessing the area and to guard against potential threats from enemy forces.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] A magazine is a place where a quantity of ammunition or other explosive material is stored temporarily before being used.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The term may be used for a facility that stores large quantities of ammunition, although this is normally referred to as an ammunition dump.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Magazines are typically located in the field for quick access when engaging the enemy.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The ammunition storage area on a warship is referred to as the "ship's magazine".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] On a smaller scale, magazine is also the name given to the ammunition storage and feeding device of a repeating firearm.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Gunpowder must be stored in a dry place (stable room temperature) to keep it usable for at least 10 years.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] It is also recommended to avoid hot places, because friction or heat might ignite a spark and cause an explosion.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The standard weapon of a modern soldier is an assault rifle, which, like other small arms, uses cartridge ammunition sized for the weapon.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Ammunition is carried on the person in box magazines specific to the weapon, ammunition boxes, pouches, or bandoliers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The amount of ammunition carried depends on the soldier's strength, the expected action required, and the ammunition's ability to move through the logistical chain to replenish the supply.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] A soldier may also carry a smaller amount of specialized ammunition for heavier weapons, such as machine guns and mortars, thereby spreading the burden of squad weapons among many people.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Too little ammunition threatens the mission, while too much limits the soldier's mobility and also threatens the mission.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] A shell is a payload-carrying projectile which, as opposed to a shot, contains explosives or other fillings, in use since the 19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Artillery shells are ammunition that is designed to be fired from artillery, which has an effect over long distances, usually indirectly (i.e., out of sight of the target).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] There are many different types of artillery ammunition, but they are usually high-explosive and designed to shatter into fragments on impact to maximize damage.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The fuze on an artillery shell can alter how it explodes or behaves, giving it a more specialized effect.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Common types of artillery ammunition include high explosive, smoke, illumination, and practice rounds.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Some artillery rounds are designed as cluster munitions.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Artillery ammunition will almost always include a projectile (the only exception being demonstration or blank rounds), fuze, and propellant of some form.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] When a cartridge case is not used, another method of containing the propellant bags is used, usually in a breech-loading weapon; see Breechloader.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Tank ammunition was developed in World War I as tanks first appeared on the battlefield.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The development of shaped charges has had a significant impact on anti-tank ammunition design, now common in both tank-fired ammunition and in anti-tank missiles, including anti-tank guided missiles.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Naval weapons were originally the same as many land-based weapons, but the ammunition was designed for specific use, such as a solid shot designed to hole an enemy ship and chain-shot to cut rigging and sails.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Modern naval engagements have occurred over far longer distances than historic battles, so as ship armor has increased in strength and thickness, the ammunition to defeat it has also changed.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Naval ammunition is now designed to reach very high velocities (to improve its armor-piercing abilities) and may have specialized fuzes to defeat specific types of vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] However, due to the extended ranges at which modern naval combat may occur, guided missiles have largely supplanted guns and shells.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] With every successive improvement in military arms, a corresponding change has occurred in the method of supplying ammunition in the required quantities.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] As soon as projectiles were required (such as javelins and arrows), there needed to be a method of replenishment.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] When non-specialized, interchangeable, or recoverable ammunition was used (e.g., arrows), it was possible to pick up spent arrows (both friendly and enemy) and reuse them.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] However, with the advent of explosive or non-recoverable ammunition, this was no longer possible, and new ammunition supplies would be needed.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The weight of ammunition required, particularly for artillery shells, can be considerable, necessitating extra time to replenish supplies.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] In modern times, there has been an increase in the standardization of many ammunition types among allies (e.g., the NATO Standardization Agreement) that has enabled the sharing of ammunition types (e.g., 5.56×45mm NATO).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] As of 2013, lead-based ammunition production is the second-largest annual use of lead in the US, accounting for over 60,000 metric tons consumed in 2012.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Lead bullets that miss their target or remain in a carcass or body that was never retrieved can enter environmental systems and become toxic to wildlife.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] The US military has experimented with replacing lead with copper as a slug in their green bullets which reduces the dangers posed by lead in the environment as a result of artillery.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Since 2010, this has eliminated over 2000 tons of lead in waste streams.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Hunters are also encouraged to use monolithic bullets, which exclude any lead content.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/ammunition] Unexploded ammunition can remain active for a very long time and poses a significant threat to both humans and the environment.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] Antony Preston was born in 1938 in Salford, Lancashire, son of the 16th Viscount Gormanston and Miss Julia O'Mahony.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] After becoming a wartime evacuee, he was educated in South Africa at King Edward VII School, Johannesburg, and the University of Witwatersrand.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] On his return to England he spent some years at the National Maritime Museum, Greenwich, before becoming Editor of the periodical *Defence*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] During the 1970s he was employed by a specialist publisher, Conway Maritime Press, as editor of their *Warship* annual.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] He also produced the specialised newsletter *Navint*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] In the early nineties, he took over as chief editor of the magazine *Naval Forces* at the German editorial group Mönch.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] He left to resume as editor of *Warships* in 1996.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] Antony Preston lived in London until his death in 2004.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/antony-preston] His son Matt Preston (born 1961 and the eldest of Preston's four children) has gained celebrity as a TV judge on *MasterChef Australia* and as a restaurant critic-columnist for the Melbourne Age & Herald-Sun newspapers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] A **frigate** (/ˈfrɪɡɪt/) is a type of warship.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In different eras, the roles and capabilities of ships classified as frigates have varied.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th to early 18th centuries the term "frigate" was loosely given to any full-rigged ship built for speed and manoeuvrability and intended for scouting, escort or patrol.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] By the second quarter of the 18th century, what is regarded as the "true frigate" was developed in France and subsequently copied by other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] This type of vessel was characterised by a long sleek design with a single gun deck of 28 and 36 cannons, and an unarmed deck below used for berthing the crew.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the mid-nineteenth century the definition of *frigate* was expanded to include the early ironclad warships, which also had a single gun deck.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] However, later developments in ironclad ships rendered the designation obsolete and the term fell out of favour in navies worldwide.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The term was reintroduced in the Second World War to describe a seagoing escort ship of intermediate size between a corvette and a destroyer.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] After the war, this definition has gradually expanded to include many different kinds of vessels, from large ocean-going anti-submarine warfare ships to corvettes, destroyers, and nuclear-powered guided-missile cruisers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The etymology of the word (Italian: *fregata*; Dutch: *fregat*; Spanish/Catalan/Portuguese/Sicilian: *fragata*; French: *frégate*; German: *Fregatte*) remains uncertain, although it may have originated as a corruption of *aphractus*, a Latin word for an open vessel with no lower deck.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] *Aphractus*, in turn, derived from the Ancient Greek phrase ἄφρακτος ναῦς (*aphraktos naus*) – "undefended ship".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The term *frigate* originated in the Mediterranean in the late 16th century, referring to a lighter galley-type warship with oars, sails and a light armament, built for speed and manoeuvrability.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The first recorded usage of the term seems to date from 1562, when Alonso Pérez, Duke of Medina Sidonia armed a galley fleet complemented with vessels called *fragatas* which were claimed to be invented by him.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] These frigates proved impractical and were retired soon.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Other sources state Medina Sidonia actually credited Álvaro de Bazán, Marquis of Santa Cruz with their invention.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The term was later used as an alternate name for the *galizabra*, a kind of galleass built by Álvaro's brother Alonso in 1584 as a cross between a galley and a zabra.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1583, during the Eighty Years' War of 1568–1648, Habsburg Spain recovered the southern Netherlands from the Protestant rebels.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] This soon resulted in the use of the occupied ports as bases for privateers, the "Dunkirkers", to attack the shipping of the Dutch and their allies.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] To achieve this the Dunkirkers developed small, manoeuvrable, sailing vessels that came to be referred to as frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In French, the term *frigate* gave rise to a verb – *frégater*, meaning 'to build long and low', and to an adjective, adding more confusion.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Even the huge English *Sovereign of the Seas* could be described as "a delicate frigate" by a contemporary after her upper decks were reduced in 1651.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The navy of the Dutch Republic became the first navy to build the larger ocean-going frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The Dutch navy had three principal tasks in the struggle against Spain: to protect Dutch merchant ships at sea, to blockade the ports of Spanish-held Flanders to damage trade and halt enemy privateering, and to fight the Spanish fleet and prevent troop landings.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The first two tasks required speed, shallowness of draft for the shallow waters around the Netherlands, and the ability to carry sufficient supplies to maintain a blockade.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The third task required heavy armament, sufficient to stand up to the Spanish fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The first of the larger battle-capable frigates were built around 1600 at Hoorn in Holland.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] By the later stages of the Eighty Years' War (1568–1648) the Dutch had switched entirely from the heavier ships still used by the English and Spanish to the lighter frigates, carrying around 40 guns and weighing around 300 tons.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th century, the term *fregat* in the Dutch Navy described any oceangoing warship carrying fewer than 40 guns.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The effectiveness of the Dutch frigates became most evident in the Battle of the Downs in 1639, encouraging most other navies, especially the English, to adopt similar designs.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The fleets built by the Commonwealth of England in the 1650s generally consisted of ships described as "frigates", the largest of which were two-decker "great frigates" of the third rate.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Carrying 60 guns, these vessels were as big and capable as "great ships" of the time; however, most other frigates at the time were used as "cruisers": independent fast ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The term "frigate" implied a long hull-design, which relates directly to speed (see hull speed) and which also, in turn, helped the development of the broadside tactic in naval warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 17th century the term 'frigate' was sometimes applied very loosely and could be used for any warship.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] At this time, a further design evolved, reintroducing oars and resulting in galley frigates such as HMS *Charles Galley* of 1676, which was rated as a 32-gun fifth-rate but also had a bank of 40 oars set below the upper deck that could propel the ship in the absence of a favourable wind.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In Danish, the word "fregat" often applied to warships carrying as few as 16 guns, such as HMS *Falcon*, which the British classified as a sloop.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Under the rating system of the Royal Navy, by the middle of the 18th century, the term "frigate" was technically restricted to single-decked ships of the fifth rate, though small 28-gun frigates were classed as sixth rate.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The classic sailing frigate, or "true frigate", well-known today for its role in the Napoleonic Wars, can be traced back to French developments in the second quarter of the 18th century.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The French-built *Médée* of 1740 is often regarded as the first example of this type.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] These ships were square-rigged and carried all their main guns on a single continuous upper deck.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The lower deck, known as the "gun deck", now carried no armament, and functioned as a "berth deck" where the crew lived, and was in fact placed below the waterline of the new frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The typical earlier cruiser had a partially armed lower deck, from which it was known as a "half-battery" or *demi-batterie* ship.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Removing the guns from this deck allowed the height of the hull upperworks to be lowered, giving the resulting "true-frigate" much improved sailing qualities.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy captured a number of the new French frigates, including *Médée*, during the War of the Austrian Succession (1740–1748) and the British were impressed by them, particularly for their inshore handling capabilities.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] They soon built copies (ordered in 1747), based on a French privateer named *Tygre*, and started to adapt the type to their own needs, setting the standard for other frigates as the leading naval power.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] However, most ships of this size were called "ship sloops".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] A total of fifty-nine French sailing frigates were built between 1777 and 1790, with a standard design averaging a hull length of 135 ft (41 m) and an average draught of 13 ft (4.0 m).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The new frigates recorded sailing speeds of up to 14 knots (26 km/h; 16 mph), significantly faster than their predecessor vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1778, the British Admiralty introduced a larger "heavy" frigate, with a main battery of twenty-six or twenty-eight 18-pounder guns (with smaller guns carried on the quarterdeck and forecastle).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] This move may reflect the naval conditions at the time; with both France and Spain as enemies, the usual British preponderance in ship numbers was no longer the case and there was pressure on the British to produce cruisers of individually greater force.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In reply, the first French 18-pounder frigates were laid down in 1781.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The 18-pounder frigate eventually became the standard frigate of the French Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The British produced larger, 38-gun, and slightly smaller, 36-gun, versions and also a 32-gun design that can be considered an 'economy version'.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The 32-gun frigates also had the advantage that they could be built by the many smaller, less-specialised shipbuilders.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates could (and usually did) additionally carry smaller carriage-mounted guns on their quarterdecks and forecastles (the superstructures above the upper deck).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1778 the Carron Iron Company of Scotland produced a naval gun which would revolutionise the armament of smaller naval vessels, including the frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The carronade was a large calibre, short-barrelled naval cannon which was light, quick to reload and needed a smaller crew than a conventional long gun.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Due to its lightness it could be mounted on the forecastle and quarterdeck of frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] It greatly increased the firepower, measured in weight of metal (the combined weight of all projectiles fired in one broadside), of these vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The disadvantages of the carronade were that it had a much shorter range and was less accurate than a long gun.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The British quickly saw the advantages of the new weapon and soon employed it on a wide scale.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The US Navy also copied the design soon after its appearance.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The French and other nations eventually adopted variations of the weapon in succeeding decades.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The typical heavy frigate had a main armament of 18-pounder long guns, plus 32-pounder carronades mounted on its upper decks.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The first "super-heavy frigates", armed with 24-pounder long guns, were built by the naval architect F H Chapman for the Swedish navy in 1782.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Because of a shortage of ships-of-the-line, the Swedes wanted these frigates, the *Bellona* class, to be able to stand in the battle line in an emergency.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] It is not known whether the French were seeking to produce very potent cruisers or merely to address stability problems in old ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The British, alarmed by the prospect of these powerful heavy frigates, responded by rasée-ing three of their smaller 64-gun battleships, including *Indefatigable*, which went on to have a very successful career as a frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] At this time the British also built a few 24-pounder-armed large frigates, the most successful of which was HMS *Endymion* (1,277 tons).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In 1797, three of the United States Navy's first six major ships were rated as 44-gun frigates, which operationally carried fifty-six to sixty 24-pounder long guns and 32-pounder or 42-pounder carronades on two decks; they were exceptionally powerful.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] USS *Constitution*, preserved as a museum ship by the US Navy, is the oldest commissioned warship afloat, and is a surviving example of a frigate from the Age of Sail.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] *Constitution* and her sister ships *President* and *United States* were created in a response to deal with the Barbary Coast pirates and in conjunction with the Naval Act of 1794.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Joshua Humphreys proposed that only live oak, a tree that grew only in America, should be used to build these ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The Admiralty, concerned by repeated defeats in single-ship actions, responded to the success of the American 44s in three ways.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] They built a class of conventional 40-gun, 24-pounder armed frigates on the lines of *Endymion*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] They cut down three old 74-gun Ships-of-the-Line into *rasées*, producing frigates with a 32-pounder main armament, supplemented by 42-pounder carronades.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] These had an armament that far exceeded the power of the American ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Finally, *Leander* and *Newcastle*, 1,500-ton spar-decked frigates (with an enclosed waist, giving a continuous line of guns from bow to stern at the level of the quarterdeck/forecastle), were built, which were an almost exact match in size and firepower to the American 44-gun frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were perhaps the hardest-worked of warship types during the Age of Sail.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] While smaller than a ship-of-the-line, they were formidable opponents for the large numbers of sloops and gunboats, not to mention privateers or merchantmen.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Able to carry six months' stores, they had very long range; and vessels larger than frigates were considered too valuable to operate independently.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates scouted for the fleet, went on commerce-raiding missions and patrols, and conveyed messages and dignitaries.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Usually, frigates would fight in small numbers or singly against other frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] They would avoid contact with ships-of-the-line; even in the midst of a fleet engagement it was bad etiquette for a ship of the line to fire on an enemy frigate which had not fired first.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were involved in fleet battles, often as "repeating frigates".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the smoke and confusion of battle, signals made by the fleet commander, whose flagship might be in the thick of the fighting, might be missed by the other ships of the fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates were therefore stationed to windward or leeward of the main line of battle, and had to maintain a clear line of sight to the commander's flagship.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Signals from the flagship were then repeated by the frigates, which themselves standing out of the line and clear from the smoke and disorder of battle, could be more easily seen by the other ships of the fleet.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] If damage or loss of masts prevented the flagship from making clear conventional signals, the repeating frigates could interpret them and hoist their own in the correct manner, passing on the commander's instructions clearly.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] For officers in the Royal Navy, a frigate was a desirable posting.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates often saw action, which meant a greater chance of glory, promotion, and prize money.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Unlike larger ships that were placed in ordinary, frigates were kept in service in peacetime as a cost-saving measure and to provide experience to frigate captains and officers which would be useful in wartime.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates could also carry marines for boarding enemy ships or for operations on shore; in 1832, the frigate USS *Potomac* landed a party of 282 sailors and Marines ashore in the US Navy's first Sumatran expedition.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates remained a crucial element of navies until the mid-19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The first ironclads were classified as "frigates" because of the number of guns they carried.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] However, terminology changed as iron and steam became the norm, and the role of the frigate was assumed first by the protected cruiser and then by the light cruiser.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates are often the vessel of choice in historical naval novels due to their relative freedom compared to ships-of-the-line (kept for fleet actions) and smaller vessels (generally assigned to a home port and less widely ranging).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] For example, the Patrick O'Brian Aubrey–Maturin series, C.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Forester's Horatio Hornblower series and Alexander Kent's Richard Bolitho series.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The 2003 film *Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World* features a reconstructed historic frigate, HMS *Rose*, to depict Aubrey's frigate HMS *Surprise*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Vessels classed as frigates continued to play a great role in navies with the adoption of steam power in the 19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the 1830s, navies experimented with large paddle steamers equipped with large guns mounted on one deck, which were termed "paddle frigates".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] From the mid-1840s on, frigates which more closely resembled the traditional sailing frigate were built with steam engines and screw propellers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] These "screw frigates", built first of wood and later of iron, continued to perform the traditional role of the frigate until late in the 19th century.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] From 1859, armour was added to ships based on existing frigate and ship of the line designs.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The additional weight of the armour on these first ironclad warships meant that they could have only one gun deck, and they were technically frigates, even though they were more powerful than existing ships-of-the-line and occupied the same strategic role.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The phrase "armoured frigate" remained in use for some time to denote a sail-equipped, broadside-firing type of ironclad.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The first such ship was the revolutionary Marine Nationale wooden-hulled *Gloire*, protected by 12 cm-thick (4.7 in) armour plates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The British response was HMS *Warrior* of the Warrior-class ironclads, launched in 1860.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] With her iron hull, steam engines propelling the 9,137 ton vessel to speeds of up to 14 knots and rifled breechloading 110-pdr guns, *Warrior* is the ancestor of all modern warships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] During the 1880s, as warship design shifted from iron to steel and cruising warships without sails started to appear, the term "frigate" fell out of use.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Vessels with armoured sides were designated as "battleships" or "armoured cruisers", while "protected cruisers" only possessed an armoured deck, and unarmoured vessels, including frigates and sloops, were classified as "unprotected cruisers".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Modern frigates are related to earlier frigates only by name.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The term "frigate" was readopted during the Second World War by the British Royal Navy to describe an anti-submarine escort vessel that was larger than a corvette (based on a mercantile design), while smaller than a destroyer.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The vessels were originally to be termed "twin screw corvettes" until the Royal Canadian Navy suggested to the British re-introducing the term "frigate" for the significantly enlarged vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates, termed destroyer escorts by the US at the time, are less expensive to build and maintain than larger destroyers and cruisers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] 22 of these were reclassified as frigates after the war, as were the remaining 24 smaller Castle-class corvettes.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate was introduced to remedy some of the shortcomings inherent in the Flower-class corvette design: limited armament, a hull form not suited to open-ocean work, a single shaft which limited speed and manoeuvrability, and a lack of range.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate was designed and built to the same mercantile construction standards (scantlings) as the corvette, allowing manufacture by yards unused to warship construction.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The first frigates of the River class (1941) were essentially two sets of corvette machinery in one larger hull, armed with the latest Hedgehog anti-submarine weapon.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate possessed less offensive firepower and speed than a destroyer, including an escort destroyer, but such qualities were not required for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Submarines were slow while submerged, and ASDIC sets did not operate effectively at speeds of over 20 knots (23 mph; 37 km/h).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Rather, the frigate was an austere and weatherly vessel suitable for mass-construction and fitted with the latest innovations in anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] As the frigate was intended purely for convoy duties, and not to deploy with the fleet, it had limited range and speed.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] It was not until the Royal Navy's Bay class of 1944 that a British design classified as a "frigate" was produced for fleet use, although it still suffered from limited speed.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] These anti-aircraft frigates, built on incomplete Loch-class frigate hulls, were similar to the United States Navy's destroyer escorts (DE), although the latter had greater speed and offensive armament to better suit them to fleet deployments.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The destroyer escort concept came from design studies by the General Board of the United States Navy in 1940, as modified by requirements established by a British commission in 1941 prior to the American entry into the war, for deep-water escorts.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The American-built destroyer escorts serving in the Royal Navy were rated as Captain-class frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy's two Canadian-built *Asheville*-class and 96 British-influenced, American-built *Tacoma*-class frigates that followed originally were classified as "patrol gunboats" (PG) in the U.S.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy but on 15 April 1943 were all reclassified as **patrol frigates (PF)**.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The introduction of the surface-to-air missile after World War II made relatively small ships effective for anti-aircraft warfare: the "guided-missile frigate".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the US navy, these vessels were called "ocean escorts" and designated "DE" or "DEG" until 1975 – a holdover from the World War II destroyer escort or "DE".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] While the Royal Navy used similar designations for their warships built in the 1950s, they maintained the use of the term "frigate"; in the 1990s the RCN re-introduced the frigate designation.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Likewise, the French Navy refers to missile-equipped ships, up to cruiser-sized ships (*Suffren*, *Tourville*, and Horizon classes), by the name of "frégate", while smaller units are named *aviso*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The Soviet Navy used the term "guard-ship" (*сторожевой корабль*).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] From the 1950s to the 1970s, the United States Navy commissioned ships classed as guided-missile frigates (hull classification symbol DLG or DLGN, literally meaning guided-missile destroyer leaders), which were actually anti-aircraft warfare cruisers built on destroyer-style hulls.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] These had one or two twin launchers per ship for the RIM-2 Terrier missile, upgraded to the RIM-67 Standard ER missile in the 1980s.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] This type of ship was intended primarily to defend aircraft carriers against anti-ship cruise missiles, augmenting and eventually replacing converted World War II cruisers (CAG/CLG/CG) in this role.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The guided-missile frigates also had an anti-submarine capability that most of the World War II cruiser conversions lacked.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Some of these ships – *Bainbridge* and *Truxtun* along with the *California* and *Virginia* classes – were nuclear-powered (DLGN).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] These "frigates" were roughly mid-way in size between cruisers and destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] This was similar to the use of the term "frigate" during the age of sail during which it referred to a medium-sized warship, but it was inconsistent with conventions used by other contemporary navies which regarded frigates as being smaller than destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the late 1970s, as a gradual successor to the *Knox* frigates, the US Navy introduced the 51-ship *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class guided-missile frigates (FFG), the last of which was decommissioned in 2015, although some serve in other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] By 1995 the older guided-missile cruisers and destroyers were replaced by the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers and *Arleigh Burke*-class destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] One of the most successful post-1945 designs was the British *Leander*-class frigate, which was used by several navies.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Laid down in 1959, the *Leander* class was based on the previous Type 12 anti-submarine frigate but equipped for anti-aircraft use as well.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] They were used by the UK into the 1990s, at which point some were sold on to other navies.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The *Leander* design, or improved versions of it, were licence-built for other navies as well.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Nearly all modern frigates are equipped with some form of offensive or defensive missiles, and as such are rated as guided-missile frigates (FFG).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Improvements in surface-to-air missiles (e.g., the Eurosam Aster 15) allow modern guided-missile frigates to form the core of many modern navies and to be used as a fleet defence platform, without the need for specialised anti-air warfare frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] They can thus provide theatre wide air and missile defence for forces such as a carrier battle group and typically serve this function".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] By contrast the smaller "frigates are thus usually used as escort vessels to protect sea lines of communication or as an auxiliary component of a strike group".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The largest and most powerful destroyers, such as the *Ticonderoga*-class cruisers, are often classified as cruisers due to their extra armament and facilities to serve as fleet flagships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy Type 61 (*Salisbury* class) were "air direction" frigates equipped to track aircraft.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] To this end they had less armament than the Type 41 (*Leopard*-class) air-defence frigates built on the same hull.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Multi-role frigates such as the MEKO 200, *Anzac* and *Halifax* classes are designed for navies needing warships deployed in a variety of situations that a general frigate class would not be able to fulfil, and not requiring destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] At the opposite end of the spectrum, some frigates are specialised for anti-submarine warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Increasing submarine speeds towards the end of World War II (see German Type XXI submarine) greatly reduced the margin of speed superiority of frigate over submarine.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The frigate could no longer be slow and powered by mercantile machinery, and consequently postwar frigates such as the *Whitby* class were faster.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Such ships carry improved sonar equipment, such as the variable depth sonar or towed array, and specialised weapons such as torpedoes, forward-throwing weapons such as Limbo and missile-carried anti-submarine torpedoes such as ASROC or Ikara.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The Royal Navy's original Type 22 frigate is an example of a specialised anti-submarine warfare frigate, though it also has Sea Wolf surface-to-air missiles for point defence plus Exocet surface-to-surface missiles for limited offensive capability.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Especially for anti-submarine warfare, most modern frigates have a landing deck and hangar aft to operate helicopters, eliminating the need for the frigate to close with unknown sub-surface threats, and using fast helicopters to attack nuclear submarines which may be faster than surface warships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] For this task the helicopter is equipped with sensors such as sonobuoys, wire-mounted dipping sonar and magnetic anomaly detectors to identify possible threats, and torpedoes or depth-charges to attack them.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] With their onboard radar helicopters can also be used to reconnoitre over-the-horizon targets and, if equipped with anti-ship missiles such as Penguin or Sea Skua, to attack them.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The helicopter is also invaluable for search and rescue operation and has largely replaced the use of small boats or the jackstay rig for such duties as transferring personnel, mail and cargo between ships or to shore.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] With helicopters these tasks can be accomplished faster and less dangerously, and without the need for the frigate to slow down or change course.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigates designed in the 1960s and 1970s, such as the US Navy's *Knox*-class frigate, West Germany's *Bremen*-class frigate, and Royal Navy's Type 22 frigate were equipped with a small number of short-ranged surface-to-air missiles (Sea Sparrow or Sea Wolf) for point defence only.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] By contrast newer frigates starting with the *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigate are specialised for "zone-defence" air defence, because of major developments in fighter jets and cruise missiles.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Recent examples include the *De Zeven Provinciën*-class air defence and command frigate of the Royal Netherlands Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Another example is the *Iver Huitfeldt* class of the Royal Danish Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Some new classes of ships similar to corvettes are optimized for high-speed deployment and combat with small craft rather than combat between equal opponents; an example is the U.S. littoral combat ship (LCS).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] As of 2015, all *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigates in the United States Navy have been decommissioned, and their role partially assumed by the new LCS.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] While the LCS class ships are smaller than the frigate class they will replace, they offer a similar degree of weaponry while requiring less than half the crew complement and offering a top speed of over 40 knots (74 km/h; 46 mph).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] A major advantage for the LCS ships is that they are designed around specific mission modules allowing them to fulfil a variety of roles.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The modular system also allows for most upgrades to be performed ashore and installed later into the ship, keeping the ships available for deployment for the maximum time.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The latest U.S. deactivation plans make this the first time that the U.S.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Navy has been without a frigate class of ships since 1943 (technically USS *Constitution* is rated as a frigate and is still in commission, but does not count towards Navy force levels).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The remaining 20 LCSs to be acquired from 2019 and onwards that will be enhanced will be designated as frigates, and existing ships given modifications may also have their classification changed to *FF* as well.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] However, the United States Navy selected a FREMM multipurpose frigate variant for a new *Constellation* class of 20 frigates, to be built by Fincantieri beginning in 2024.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Stealth technology has been introduced in modern frigate design by the French *La Fayette* class design.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Frigate shapes are designed to offer a minimal radar cross section, which also lends them good air penetration; the manoeuvrability of these frigates has been compared to that of sailing ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The modern French Navy applies the term first-class frigate and second-class frigate to both destroyers and frigates in service.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Pennant numbers remain divided between F-series numbers for those ships internationally recognised as frigates and D-series pennant numbers for those more traditionally recognised as destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] This can result in some confusion as certain classes are referred to as frigates in French service while similar ships in other navies are referred to as destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] This also results in some recent classes of French ships such as the Horizon class being among the largest in the world to carry the rating of frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The *Frégates de Taille Intermédiaire* (FTI), which means frigates of intermediate size, is a French military program to design and create a planned class of frigates to be used by the French Navy.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] At the moment, the program consists of five ships, with commissioning planned from 2023.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] In the German Navy, frigates were used to replace ageing destroyers; however in size and role the new German frigates exceed the former class of destroyers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The current German F125 Baden-Württemberg-class frigates are the largest class of frigates worldwide with a displacement of more than 7,200 tons .
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The same was done in the Spanish Navy, which went ahead with the deployment of the first Aegis frigates, the *Álvaro de Bazán*-class frigates.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The Myanmar Navy is producing modern frigates with a reduced radar cross section known as the Kyan Sittha-class frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Before the Kyan Sittha class, the Myanmar Navy also produced an *Aung Zeya*-class frigate.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] Although the size of the Myanmar Navy is quite small, it is producing modern guided-missile frigates with the help of Russia, China, and India.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] However, the fleets of the Myanmar Navy are still expanding with several on-going shipbuilding programmes, including one 135 m (442 ft 11 in), 4,000-tonne frigate with the vertical missile launch systems.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] The four planned *Tamandaré*-class frigates of the Brazilian Navy will be responsible for introducing ships with stealth technology in the national navy and the Latin American region, with the first boat expected to be launched in 2024.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] A few frigates have survived as museum ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/armoured-frigate-p01] These ships are classified by their respective nations as frigates, but are considered destroyers internationally due to size, armament, and role.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] Collaborating with Charles Renard, Krebs piloted the first fully controlled free-flight made in the French Army airship *La France*, which was designed in 1884.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight covered 8 km (5.0 mi) in 23 minutes.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] The flight landed back at its starting point.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] On its seven flights the *La France* dirigible returned five times to its starting point.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs and Renard shared the 1886 Ponti prize of the French *Académie des sciences* for their contribution to aerostation.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In Verne's 1886 novel *Robur The Conqueror*, he writes of "the striking experiments of Captain Krebs and Captain Renard".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1888 Krebs and Gustave Zédé designed the first modern French submarine, the *Gymnote*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] The submarine was fitted with the first naval periscope and the first naval electric gyrocompass.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] The latter allowed the *Gymnote* to force a naval block in 1890.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] From 1884 to 1897 Arthur Krebs modernized the *Ville de Paris* fire department; not only its equipment but its organisation as well.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] His work left a lasting impression in this elite corps.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In May 1896 Arthur Krebs patented a new automobile, fitted with an electromagnetic gearbox and a layout of the front wheels which re-centred them when the steering wheel was left alone.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] Today this is known as the Castor angle.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] The Panhard et Levassor company acquired a license to build 500 cars under the name of Clement-Panhard between 1898 and 1902 featuring this innovation.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs succeeded Levassor as Panhard et Levassor's general manager from 1897 to 1916.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] He transformed the Panhard et Levassor Company into one of the largest and most profitable automobile manufacturers before World War I.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1898 Krebs replaced the tiller with an inclined steering wheel for the Panhard et Levassor car he designed for the Paris-Amsterdam race which ran from 7 to 13 July 1898.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] Fernand Charron won that race on a four-cylinder Panhard et Levassor.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] At the end of 1898, C S Rolls introduced the first car in Britain fitted with wheel steering when he imported a 6 hp Panhard et Levassor from France.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1902 Krebs invented the automatic diaphragm carburettor which gave cars continuous power during acceleration by providing a constant air-fuel ratio at all times; this also led to dramatic improvement in fuel economy.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1906 Krebs traveled to the United States to plead in the Selden Case, associated with Henry Ford.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] Also, Krebs contributed significantly to improve the Systeme Panhard (engine in front, rear wheel drive) which became universally adopted before World War II.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1909 Krebs became interested in the Knight patent (sleeve valve engine).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] He was also the first person in France to build that type of engine which Panhard et Levassor would produce during the thirty years leading up to World War II.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] He made contributions to automotive racing with his powerful cars and motorboats.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911 Krebs invented the first elastomeric flexible coupling (cf.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] It is known in French as the *Flector* joint.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] This device is still widely used today in industry for power transmission as a *tyre coupling*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck was meant for military and civil purposes.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1911, jointly with the Chatillon Co, Krebs designed the *Tracteur Chatillon-Panhard* all-terrain truck.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] The truck had four wheel drive and four wheel steering and many were used during World War I as artillery tractors.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] Krebs also utilized his former military membership to supply the French Army with engines and vehicles including the 1904 Genty Armored car, the 1916 St Chamond tank, the Chatillon-Panhard 4x4 truck, and others.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1960, the United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee (UK-APC) named Krebs Glacier, a glacier flowing west into the head of Charlotte Bay on the west coast of Graham Land in the Antarctic continent, after Krebs.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/arthur-constantin-krebs] In 1934, several months before Arthur Krebs's death, he was made a Commandeur of the Legion of Honour for his work in Aeronautics and for his contributions to the automotive industry.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/barquentine] A **barquentine** or **schooner barque** (alternatively "barkentine" or "schooner bark") is a sailing vessel with three or more masts, with a square rigged foremast and fore-and-aft rigged main, mizzen and any other masts.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/barquentine] While a full-rigged ship is square-rigged on all three masts, and the barque is square-rigged except for the mizzen-mast, the barquentine extends the principle by making only the foremast square-rigged.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/barquentine] The advantages of a smaller crew, good performance before the wind and the ability to sail relatively close to the wind while carrying plenty of cargo made it a popular rig at the end of the nineteenth century.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/barquentine] Today, barquentines are popular with modern tall ship and sail training operators as their suite of mainly fore-and-aft sails improve non-downwind performance, while their foremast of square sails offers long distance downwind speed and dramatic appearance in port.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/barquentine] The term "barquentine" is seventeenth-century in origin, formed from "barque" in imitation of "brigantine", a two-masted vessel square-rigged only on the forward mast, and apparently formed from the word brig.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The **Battle of Sinop**, or the **Battle of Sinope**, was a naval battle that took place on 30 November 1853 between Imperial Russia and the Ottoman Empire during the opening phase of the Crimean War (1853–1856).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] It took place at Sinop, a sea port on the southern shore of the Black Sea (the northern shore of Anatolian Turkey).
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] A Russian squadron attacked and decisively defeated an Ottoman squadron anchored in Sinop's harbor.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The Russian force consisted of six ships of the line, two frigates and three armed steamers, led by Admiral Pavel Nakhimov; the Ottoman defenders were seven frigates, three corvettes and two armed steamers, commanded by Vice Admiral Osman Pasha.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The Russian navy had recently adopted naval artillery that fired explosive shells, which gave them a decisive advantage in the battle.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] All the Ottoman frigates and corvettes were either sunk or forced to run aground to avoid destruction; only one steamer escaped.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Nearly 3,000 Turks were killed when Nakhimov's forces fired on the town after the battle.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The victory is commemorated in Russia as one of the Days of Military Honour.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The one-sided battle contributed to the decision of France and Britain to enter the war, on the side of the Ottomans.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The battle demonstrated the effectiveness of explosive shells against wooden hulls, and the superiority of shells over cannonballs.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] It led to widespread adoption of explosive naval artillery and indirectly to the development of ironclad warships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] On 4 October 1853, around 2 months before the battle, in response to the Russian occupation of Moldavia and Wallachia (then part of the Ottoman Danube), the Ottoman Empire declared war on Russia.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] By the early 1850s the Ottoman Empire was deeply in debt and relied exclusively on British and French loans as a means of support.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] As a result, Ottoman leaders had no choice but to agree to drastic reductions in both army and navy force levels.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Tsar Nicholas I saw the reductions as an opportunity to press Russian claims in the Trans-Caucasus and along the Danube River.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] In July 1853 Russian forces occupied several Ottoman principalities and forts along the Danube.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Mediation of the disputes broke down, and Ottoman Sultan Abdulmecid I responded with a declaration of war.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Fearing Russian expansion, the United Kingdom and France issued a concurrent ultimatum: Russia was to fight only defensively.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] As long as Russia stayed on the defensive the Anglo-French would remain neutral, but if Russia acted "aggressively" the western powers reserved the right to get involved.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Hostilities began officially on 4 October, with a principal theater in Europe and another in the Caucasus.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Sultan Abdulmecid ordered an immediate offensive to drive back the Russians and demonstrate Ottoman might before Ottoman finances totally collapsed.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The offensive along the Danube met with mixed success, but the Ottoman land attack into the Russian Caucasus was relatively successful.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] By the end of October, the Russian Caucasus Corps was in danger of being surrounded.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Turkish ships trafficking gunpowder to the Circassians were in contravention of the Straits Convention, which international law was sworn to uphold.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The Russians told the Austrian Consul that they were legitimately entitled to seek redress for this act of piracy.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Furthermore Russia claimed that two Customs House men had been murdered at Tiflis.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The tsar needed no further incentive to react.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Despite the Ottoman declaration of war, the naval aspect was mostly uneventful until November, when the Vice Admiral Osman Pasha was forced to dock at Sinop during a storm on the Black Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] To support the attack and properly supply his forces before significant snowfall, Sultan Abdulmecid ordered a squadron of frigates, steamers and transports to establish a supply corridor to the Ottoman army in Georgia.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Osman Pasha, himself aboard the 60-gun *Avni Illah*, had been sailing with seven frigates, two corvettes and several transports to resupply the Turkish land forces.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Unable to interdict the convoy, Russian naval elements remained in Sevastopol.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Abdulmecid ordered a second convoy commanded by Osman Pasha, but by this time it was late November and the fleet was forced to seek winter quarters.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] It ended up at Sinop, joining the frigate *Kaid Zafer* which had been part of an earlier patrol, and was joined by the steam frigate *Taif* from a smaller squadron.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The Ottomans had wanted to send ships of the line to Sinop, but the British ambassador in Constantinople, Viscount Stratford de Redcliffe, had objected to this plan, and only frigates were sent.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Initial Ottoman activity in the Black Sea had been allowed to proceed unhindered, but as the situation of the Russian Caucasus Corps deteriorated, St.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Pavel Nakhimov was ordered to muster the Russian navy and interdict the Ottomans.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] From 1–23 November Russian squadrons were dispatched into the Black Sea to establish control.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Two Ottoman steamers, the *Medzhir Tadzhiret* and the *Pervaz Bahri*, were captured by the Russians in short engagements.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Russia was able to establish operational control of the sea lanes but storms forced Nakhimov to send back most of his force for repair.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Left with only a frigate, a steamer and three ships of the line, Nakhimov continued the search for Osman and the convoy.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] On 23 November, Osman's flag was sighted returning and then entering the harbor at Sinop.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Nakhimov immediately deployed his ships to blockade the harbor and sent his only frigate to retrieve as many reinforcements as could be found.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] On 30 November, Vice Admiral Fyodor Novosilski rallied six more ships to Nakhimov, completing the blockade force in a loose semi-circle.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Additional steamers were expected, but Nakhimov decided to act before the Ottomans could be reinforced by additional ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] For his part, Osman had been well aware of the Russian presence since 23 November, but felt his ships were safe in harbor.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Sinop had substantial harbor defenses and forts with interlocking fields of fire and ample cannon.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Osman did little to break the weak Russian blockade, even allowing many of his crews to disembark.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Three Russian second-rate ships of the line (84 cannons each) led by Admiral Nakhimov arrived at Sinop on 23 November to discover the Turkish fleet in the harbor under the defence of the on-shore fortifications strengthened by cannons.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Six Russian warships from Sevastopol under command of Vice Admiral Fyodor Novosilsky (including three 120-cannon first-rate ships of the line) joined Nakhimov on 28 November.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Admiral Nakhimov, was under orders from Alexander Sergeyevich Menshikov to destroy any Turkish ships carrying supplies to the Caucasus.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] His squadron included six modern battleships, two frigates, and three streamers, with the heavier Paixhans guns armed with explosive shells, their first use in a sea battle.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The Ottoman forces included seven frigates, three corvettes and two armed steamers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The Russians planned to deploy their ships in two columns that would advance to within close range of the enemy vessels before dropping anchor and opening fire.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Under Nakhimov's command, the 84-gun ship *Imperatritsa Maria* was the first to engage when she fired on the 44-gun Ottoman flagship *Auni Allah*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] On 30 November the Russian squadron entered the harbor from the northwest in a triangular formation.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Nakhimov maneuvered his fleet so that the Ottoman vessels were between the Russian ships and Sinop's harbor defenses, shielding his own force and exposing the Ottomans to potential friendly fire.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Nakhimov spaced his battleships evenly in two lines, covering the entire harbor with interlocking fields of fire.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Russian gunners began to score hits on all the Ottoman targets.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The projectile shells fired for the first time from Russian guns immediately set the wooden Ottoman ships on fire.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Panic-stricken sailors found firefighting efforts difficult amidst continued fire and almost constant shrapnel.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] After about 30 minutes of combat the Ottoman flag frigate *Auni Allah* was shot full of holes and ran aground when her anchor cable was cut.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] *Imperatritsa Maria* then attacked and disabled the 44-gun frigate *Fazli Allah*, which caught fire.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Meanwhile, the other Russian ships damaged the *Nizamie* and *Damiad*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The Ottoman corvette *Guli Sephid* and frigate *Navek Bakhri* exploded.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Only one Ottoman vessel, the 12-gun paddle frigate *Taif*, managed to escape the battle while all the others were either sunk or purposely run ashore to prevent sinking.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] She fled to Istanbul and arrived on 2 December, informing the Ottoman government and Admiral Stratford of the Royal Navy of the defeat at Sinop.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Once the enemy fleet was destroyed the Russians engaged Ottoman shore batteries and destroyed them.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] During the fighting 37 Russians were killed and 229 were wounded, and at least three of the ships of the line were damaged.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Ottoman casualties included 2700 sailors killed of the 4200 present, while Sinop endured six days of bombardment.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] When telegraph reports of the battle reached Russian authorities in St.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The untested and widely hated Russian navy had proven victorious and the recent expenditure in its development seemed warranted.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Several balls were held to celebrate the victory and a state-funded parade was held.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The affair was rather grand, and included dancers, bands, parading troops who had not taken part in the battle and criminals dressed up in Ottoman uniforms.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Military advisors saw the battle as a turning point and pushed for shell-firing guns to be installed on all Russian ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The reaction in the Ottoman capital of Constantinople ranged from concern to total panic.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Russia had annihilated a vital convoy and now had operational control over the Black Sea.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The destruction of the harbor defenses opened the door to Russian invasion and suddenly the entire Samsun and Trabzon Coast was now at risk.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Moreover, the Russian violation of the British/French mandate for the war meant that the actions of Russia could no longer be predicted and Russia might not be fighting with one hand tied behind its back.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The attack was treated by external powers as unjustified and caused a wave of anti-Russian sentiment in western Europe.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Much of the British press presented the attack as the "Massacre of Sinope".
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The attack strengthened the pro-war factions in Britain and France, and provided them with the justification for a war to curb Russian bellicosity.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Lord Palmerston temporarily resigned over the affair.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] By March 1854, however, war hawks in the National Government won out and Sinop was seen as a just cause for war, although ultimately the real motivation was to curb Russian expansion in accordance with a balance of power strategy.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] "Turkey must be defended from aggression....
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Sinop was presented by the media as not so much a battle but an ambush, but its results were nonetheless important to the practice of 19th-century warfare and the evolution of naval doctrine.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Prior to Sinop the standard naval armament was the smooth-bore that fired cannonballs, shot, shrapnel, and other projectiles.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Paixhans guns or regional equivalents were slowly being integrated into navies, but only the French, Russian and American navies had made a comprehensive effort.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] These batteries represented a clear evolution in naval technology that broke through the final ceiling of the Age of Sail.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Unlike previous smooth-bore ordnance, Paixhans guns fired explosive shells and not mere metal projectiles.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The shells themselves did both kinetic and explosive damage, causing fires.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] In addition, the new guns were heavier, could engage at a greater range, and possessed far greater penetrating power.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] However, until 1853 no navy had made comprehensive use of shell-firing guns in a live combat environment.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] Indeed, many experts disparaged the new weapons and the larger ships required to carry them as too heavy for naval warfare.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] The results of Sinop were clear and showed that the new weapons were effective.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/battle-of-sinop] As a result, an arms race ensued with participant nations desperately looking for ways to up-gun existing ships and incorporate the shell-firing guns into new ironclad vessels.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] The **French ironclad *Gloire*** (French pronunciation: [ɡlwaʁ], "Glory") was the first ocean-going ironclad, launched in 1859.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] She was developed after the Crimean War, in response to new developments of naval gun technology, especially the Paixhans guns and rifled guns, which used explosive shells with increased destructive power against wooden ships.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] Her design was also influenced by the Anglo-French development of ironclad floating batteries to bombard Russian forts during the same war.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] Reports regarding the construction of *Gloire* reached France's British rivals in May 1858.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] This led to the construction of the armoured frigate HMS *Warrior*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] The ship underwent preliminary trials in June 1860 with official trials on 20-21 of August, where she achieved 13.5 knots.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] In September of that year, she escorted the imperial yacht *Aigle* carrying Emperor Napoleon III to Algiers.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] During a storm on the return voyage, the *Gloire* was the sole escort able to remain with the *Aigle*.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] On 12 November, *Gloire* began comparative trials with the *Algésiras,* culminating in a trial report on 30 March 1861.
[src:french-ironclad-gloire/french-ironclad-gloire] As the first ocean-going ironclad, *Gloire* rendered obsolete traditional unarmoured wooden ships-of-the-line, and all major navies soon began to build ironclads of their own.
